{{ill|Koichi Mori|ja|森浩一}} suggested that the centrally sunken wooden board, measuring 3 meters in length as mentioned above, is likely the bottom of a {{ill|Bamboo-split Wooden Coffin|ja|割竹形木棺}}, although he also noted the possibility that a log boat was used as a coffin, and he could not conclusively determine which was the case. The 1912 excavation was carried out at the initiative of the landowner and was not strictly a scholarly investigation; in truth, {{ill|Tsuboi Shogo|ja|坪井正五郎}} was merely summoned to attend and provide his opinion, and the excavation report was nothing more than an article contributed by a newspaper reporter covering the excavation for an "Archaeology Magazine". Furthermore, the excavation was hastily concluded in just two days, and immediately afterward, a telegram was sent from the {{ill|Imperial Household Ministry Burial Office|ja|宮内省諸陵寮}} (currently {{ill|Imperial Household Agency Burial Office|ja|宮内庁書陵部}}) ordering its suspension, following information that an unregistered accompanying mound had been excavated. Additionally, {{ill|Katsumi Kuroban|ja|黒板勝美}}—a lecturer in national history at Tokyo Imperial University, like Tsuboi—harshly criticized this excavation in the same issue of the Archaeology Magazine that published the report on the Tsukamawari Kofun, and he submitted a paper arguing that legislation should be enacted to restrict kofun excavations. Moreover, a lawsuit continued for some time between the government and the landowner over the ownership of the excavated burial goods <ref>Mori (1965) pp.47-51</ref>.

